# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: e-h-moore
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] A first generation American, he was born in Chicago and most associated with that city.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He received his Bachelor of Science in 1926, Masters in 1927, and PhD in 1928, at the age of 22.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] All degrees were obtained from the University of Chicago.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He married around the same time as his graduation.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He spent his postdoctoral year at Princeton University and then from 1929 to 1931 he was an instructor at Columbia University.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] During this period he worked on Abelian varieties and their endomorphism algebras.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He returned to Princeton for the opening year of the Institute for Advanced Study in 1933-34 and spent another year in Princeton in 1961–62 as the first Director of the Communications Research Division of the Institute for Defense Analyses (IDA).
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He later served on the Board of Trustees of IDA 1969–1972.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] From 1931 to 1972, he served on the mathematics faculty at the University of Chicago, where he became chair of the Mathematics Department in 1958 and Dean of the Physical Sciences Division in 1961.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] As an applied mathematician, he also did work for the military during World War II and thereafter.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] One of his most notable achievements was his groundbreaking work on cryptography.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He prepared a manuscript, "Some Mathematical Aspects of Cryptography", for his invited address at a meeting of the American Mathematical Society in November 1941.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] The theory that developed from this work can be seen in digital communications technologies.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] After WWII, he became a forceful advocate favoring government support for research in mathematics on a par with physical sciences.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] He served on policy-making bodies at the Office of Naval Research, the United States National Research Council, and the National Science Foundation that funneled research grants into mathematics, giving many young mathematicians career opportunities previously unavailable.
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] Due to his success in helping to give mathematical research a sound financial footing, he earned the title of "statesman for mathematics".
[src:e-h-moore/abraham-adrian-albert] Albert was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1968.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In mathematics, more specifically algebra, **abstract algebra** or **modern algebra** is the study of algebraic structures, which are sets with specific operations acting on their elements.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures include groups, rings, fields, modules, vector spaces, lattices, and algebras over a field.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The term *abstract algebra* was coined in the early 20th century to distinguish it from older parts of algebra, and more specifically from elementary algebra, the use of variables to represent numbers in computation and reasoning.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The abstract perspective on algebra has become so fundamental to advanced mathematics that it is simply called "algebra", while the term "abstract algebra" is seldom used except in pedagogy.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures, with their associated homomorphisms, form mathematical categories.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Category theory gives a unified framework to study properties and constructions that are similar for various structures.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Universal algebra is a related subject that studies types of algebraic structures as single objects.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For example, the structure of groups is a single object in universal algebra, which is called the *variety of groups*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Before the nineteenth century, algebra was defined as the study of polynomials.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra came into existence during the nineteenth century as more complex problems and solution methods developed.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Concrete problems and examples came from number theory, geometry, analysis, and the solutions of algebraic equations.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] This unification occurred in the early decades of the 20th century and resulted in the formal axiomatic definitions of various algebraic structures such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] This historical development is almost the opposite of the treatment found in popular textbooks, such as van der Waerden's *Moderne Algebra*, which start each chapter with a formal definition of a structure and then follow it with concrete examples.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The study of polynomial equations or algebraic equations has a long history.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Circa 1700 BC, the Babylonians were able to solve quadratic equations specified as word problems.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] This word problem stage is classified as rhetorical algebra and was the dominant approach up to the 16th century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Al-Khwarizmi originated the word "algebra" in 830 AD, but his work was entirely rhetorical algebra.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Fully symbolic algebra did not appear until François Viète's 1591 New Algebra, and even this had some spelled out words that were given symbols in Descartes's 1637 *La Géométrie*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The formal study of solving symbolic equations led Leonhard Euler to accept what were then considered "nonsense" roots such as negative numbers and imaginary numbers, in the late 18th century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] However, European mathematicians, for the most part, resisted these concepts until the middle of the 19th century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] George Peacock's 1830 *Treatise of Algebra* was the first attempt to place algebra on a strictly symbolic basis.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He distinguished a new symbolical algebra, distinct from the old arithmetical algebra.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Whereas in arithmetical algebra $a-b$ is restricted to $a\geq b$ , in symbolical algebra all rules of operations hold with no restrictions.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Using this Peacock could show laws such as $(-a)(-b)=ab$ , by letting $d=0,c=0$ in $(d-b)(c-a)=dc+ba-ad-bc$ .
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Peacock used what he termed the principle of the permanence of equivalent forms to justify his argument, but his reasoning suffered from the problem of induction.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For example, ${\sqrt {a}}{\sqrt {b}}={\sqrt {ab}}$ holds for the nonnegative real numbers, but not for general complex numbers.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Several areas of mathematics led to the study of groups.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Lagrange's 1770 study of the solutions of the quintic equation led to the Galois group of a polynomial.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Gauss's 1801 study of Fermat's little theorem led to the ring of integers modulo n, the multiplicative group of integers modulo n, and the more general concepts of cyclic groups and abelian groups.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Klein's 1872 Erlangen program studied geometry and led to symmetry groups such as the Euclidean group and the group of projective transformations.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1874 Lie introduced the theory of Lie groups, aiming for "the Galois theory of differential equations".
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1876 Poincaré and Klein introduced the group of Möbius transformations, and its subgroups such as the modular group and Fuchsian group, based on work on automorphic functions in analysis.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The abstract concept of group emerged slowly over the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Galois in 1832 was the first to use the term "group", signifying a collection of permutations closed under composition.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Arthur Cayley's 1854 paper *On the theory of groups* defined a group as a set with an associative composition operation and the identity 1, today called a monoid.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1870 Kronecker defined an abstract binary operation that was closed, commutative, associative, and had the left cancellation property $b\neq c\to a\cdot b\neq a\cdot c$ , similar to the modern laws for a finite abelian group.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Weber's 1882 definition of a group was a closed binary operation that was associative and had left and right cancellation.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Walther von Dyck in 1882 was the first to require inverse elements as part of the definition of a group.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Once this abstract group concept emerged, results were reformulated in this abstract setting.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For example, Sylow's theorem was reproven by Frobenius in 1887 directly from the laws of a finite group, although Frobenius remarked that the theorem followed from Cauchy's theorem on permutation groups and the fact that every finite group is a subgroup of a permutation group.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Otto Hölder was particularly prolific in this area, defining quotient groups in 1889, group automorphisms in 1893, as well as simple groups.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He also completed the Jordan–Hölder theorem.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Dedekind and Miller independently characterized Hamiltonian groups and introduced the notion of the commutator of two elements.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Burnside, Frobenius, and Molien created the representation theory of finite groups at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] A. de Séguier's 1905 monograph *Elements of the Theory of Abstract Groups* presented many of these results in an abstract, general form, relegating "concrete" groups to an appendix, although it was limited to finite groups.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The first monograph on both finite and infinite abstract groups was O.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Schmidt's 1916 *Abstract Theory of Groups*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Noncommutative ring theory began with extensions of the complex numbers to hypercomplex numbers, specifically William Rowan Hamilton's quaternions in 1843.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Many other number systems followed shortly.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1844, Hamilton presented biquaternions, Cayley introduced octonions, and Grassman introduced exterior algebras.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] James Cockle presented tessarines in 1848 and coquaternions in 1849.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] William Kingdon Clifford introduced split-biquaternions in 1873.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In addition Cayley introduced group algebras over the real and complex numbers in 1854 and square matrices in two papers of 1855 and 1858.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Once there were sufficient examples, it remained to classify them.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In an 1870 monograph, Benjamin Peirce classified the more than 150 hypercomplex number systems of dimension below 6, and gave an explicit definition of an associative algebra.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He defined nilpotent and idempotent elements and proved that any algebra contains one or the other.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He also defined the Peirce decomposition.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Frobenius in 1878 and Charles Sanders Peirce in 1881 independently proved that the only finite-dimensional division algebras over $\mathbb {R}$ were the real numbers, the complex numbers, and the quaternions.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In the 1880s Killing and Cartan showed that semisimple Lie algebras could be decomposed into simple ones, and classified all simple Lie algebras.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Cartan was the first to define concepts such as direct sum and simple algebra, and these concepts proved quite influential.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1907 Wedderburn extended Cartan's results to an arbitrary field, in what are now called the Wedderburn principal theorem and Artin–Wedderburn theorem.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For commutative rings, several areas together led to commutative ring theory.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In two papers in 1828 and 1832, Gauss formulated the Gaussian integers and showed that they form a unique factorization domain (UFD) and proved the biquadratic reciprocity law.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Jacobi and Eisenstein at around the same time proved a cubic reciprocity law for the Eisenstein integers.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The study of Fermat's Last Theorem led to the algebraic integers.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1847, Gabriel Lamé thought he had proven FLT, but his proof was faulty as he assumed all the cyclotomic fields were UFDs, yet as Kummer pointed out, $\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{23}))$ was not a UFD.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1846 and 1847 Kummer introduced ideal numbers and proved unique factorization into ideal primes for cyclotomic fields.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Dedekind extended this in 1871 to show that every nonzero ideal in the domain of integers of an algebraic number field is a unique product of prime ideals, a precursor of the theory of Dedekind domains.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Overall, Dedekind's work created the subject of algebraic number theory.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In the 1850s, Riemann introduced the fundamental concept of a Riemann surface.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Riemann's methods relied on an assumption he called Dirichlet's principle, which in 1870 was questioned by Weierstrass.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Much later, in 1900, Hilbert justified Riemann's approach by developing the direct method in the calculus of variations.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In the 1860s and 1870s, Clebsch, Gordan, Brill, and especially M.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Noether studied algebraic functions and curves.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In particular, Noether studied what conditions were required for a polynomial to be an element of the ideal generated by two algebraic curves in the polynomial ring $\mathbb {R} [x,y]$ , although Noether did not use this modern language.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1882 Dedekind and Weber, in analogy with Dedekind's earlier work on algebraic number theory, created a theory of algebraic function fields which allowed the first rigorous definition of a Riemann surface and a rigorous proof of the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Kronecker in the 1880s, Hilbert in 1890, Lasker in 1905, and Macaulay in 1913 further investigated the ideals of polynomial rings implicit in E.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Lasker proved a special case of the Lasker-Noether theorem, namely that every ideal in a polynomial ring is a finite intersection of primary ideals.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Macaulay proved the uniqueness of this decomposition.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Overall, this work led to the development of algebraic geometry.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced binary quadratic forms over the integers and defined their equivalence.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He further defined the discriminant of these forms, which is an invariant of a binary form.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Between the 1860s and 1890s invariant theory developed and became a major field of algebra.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Cayley, Sylvester, Gordan and others found the Jacobian and the Hessian for binary quartic forms and cubic forms.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1868 Gordan proved that the graded algebra of invariants of a binary form over the complex numbers was finitely generated, i.e., has a basis.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Hilbert wrote a thesis on invariants in 1885 and in 1890 showed that any form of any degree or number of variables has a basis.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He extended this further in 1890 to Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Once these theories had been developed, it was still several decades until an abstract ring concept emerged.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The first axiomatic definition was given by Abraham Fraenkel in 1914.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] His definition was mainly the standard axioms: a set with two operations addition, which forms a group (not necessarily commutative), and multiplication, which is associative, distributes over addition, and has an identity element.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In addition, he had two axioms on "regular elements" inspired by work on the p-adic numbers, which excluded now-common rings such as the ring of integers.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] These allowed Fraenkel to prove that addition was commutative.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Fraenkel's work aimed to transfer Steinitz's 1910 definition of fields over to rings, but it was not connected with the existing work on concrete systems.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Masazo Sono's 1917 definition was the first equivalent to the present one.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1920, Emmy Noether, in collaboration with W.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Schmeidler, published a paper about the theory of ideals in which they defined left and right ideals in a ring.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The following year she published a landmark paper called *Idealtheorie in Ringbereichen* (*Ideal theory in rings'*), analyzing ascending chain conditions with regard to (mathematical) ideals.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The publication gave rise to the term "Noetherian ring", and several other mathematical objects being called *Noetherian*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Noted algebraist Irving Kaplansky called this work "revolutionary"; results which seemed inextricably connected to properties of polynomial rings were shown to follow from a single axiom.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Artin, inspired by Noether's work, came up with the descending chain condition.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] These definitions marked the birth of abstract ring theory.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced the integers mod p, where p is a prime number.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Galois extended this in 1830 to finite fields with $p^{n}$ elements.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1871 Richard Dedekind introduced, for a set of real or complex numbers that is closed under the four arithmetic operations, the German word *Körper*, which means "body" or "corpus" (to suggest an organically closed entity).
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The English term "field" was introduced by Moore in 1893.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1881 Leopold Kronecker defined what he called a *domain of rationality*, which is a field of rational fractions in modern terms.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The first clear definition of an abstract field was due to Heinrich Martin Weber in 1893.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] It was missing the associative law for multiplication, but covered finite fields and the fields of algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In 1910 Steinitz synthesized the knowledge of abstract field theory accumulated so far.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] He axiomatically defined fields with the modern definition, classified them by their characteristic, and proved many theorems commonly seen today.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The end of the 19th and the beginning of the 20th century saw a change in the methodology of mathematics.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra emerged around the start of the 20th century, under the name *modern algebra*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Its study was part of the drive for more intellectual rigor in mathematics.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Initially, the assumptions in classical algebra, on which the whole of mathematics (and major parts of the natural sciences) depend, took the form of axiomatic systems.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] No longer satisfied with establishing properties of concrete objects, mathematicians started to turn their attention to general theory.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions of certain algebraic structures began to emerge in the 19th century.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For example, results about various groups of permutations came to be seen as instances of general theorems that concern a general notion of an *abstract group*.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Questions of structure and classification of various mathematical objects came to the forefront.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] These processes were occurring throughout all of mathematics but became especially noticeable in algebra.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions through primitive operations and axioms were proposed for many basic algebraic structures, such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Hence such things as group theory and ring theory took their places in pure mathematics.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] By abstracting away various amounts of detail, mathematicians have defined various algebraic structures that are used in many areas of mathematics.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For instance, almost all systems studied are sets, to which the theorems of set theory apply.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Those sets that have a certain binary operation defined on them form magmas, to which the concepts concerning magmas, as well those concerning sets, apply.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] We can add additional constraints on the algebraic structure, such as associativity (to form semigroups); identity, and inverses (to form groups); and other more complex structures.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] With additional structure, more theorems could be proved, but the generality is reduced.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In general there is a balance between the amount of generality and the richness of the theory: more general structures have usually fewer nontrivial theorems and fewer applications.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] A group is a set G together with a "group product", a binary operation $\cdot :G\times G\rightarrow G$ .
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] A ring is a set R with two binary operations, addition: $(x,y)\mapsto x+y,$ and multiplication: $(x,y)\mapsto xy$ satisfying the following axioms.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Because of its generality, abstract algebra is used in many fields of mathematics and science.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] For instance, algebraic topology uses algebraic objects to study topologies.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] The Poincaré conjecture, proved in 2003, asserts that the fundamental group of a manifold, which encodes information about connectedness, can be used to determine whether a manifold is a sphere or not.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Algebraic number theory studies various number rings that generalize the set of integers.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] Using tools of algebraic number theory, Andrew Wiles proved Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In physics, groups are used to represent symmetry operations, and the usage of group theory could simplify differential equations.
[src:e-h-moore/abstract-algebra] In gauge theory, the requirement of local symmetry can be used to deduce the equations describing a system.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:e-h-moore/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:e-h-moore/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:e-h-moore/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Moore, the son of a Methodist minister and grandson of US Congressman Eliakim H.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Moore, discovered mathematics through a summer job at the Cincinnati Observatory while in high school.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He subsequently studied mathematics at Yale University, where he was a member of Skull and Bones and obtained a BA in 1883 and the PhD in 1885 with a thesis supervised by Hubert Anson Newton, on some work of William Kingdon Clifford and Arthur Cayley.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Newton encouraged Moore to study in Germany, and thus he spent an academic year at the University of Berlin, attending lectures by Leopold Kronecker and Karl Weierstrass.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] On his return to the United States, Moore taught at Yale and at Northwestern University.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] When the University of Chicago opened its doors in 1892, Moore was the first head of its mathematics department, a position he retained until his death in 1932.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] His first two colleagues were Oskar Bolza and Heinrich Maschke.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] The resulting department was the second research-oriented mathematics department in American history, after Johns Hopkins University.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Moore first worked in abstract algebra, proving in 1893 the classification of the structure of finite fields (also called Galois fields).
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Around 1900, he began working on the foundations of geometry.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He reformulated Hilbert's axioms for geometry so that points were the only primitive notion, thus turning David Hilbert's primitive lines and planes into defined notions.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] In 1902, he further showed that one of Hilbert's axioms for geometry was redundant.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] His work on axiom systems is considered one of the starting points for metamathematics and model theory.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] After 1906, he turned to the foundations of analysis.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] The concept of a closure operator first appeared in his 1910 *Introduction to a form of general analysis*.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He also wrote on algebraic geometry, number theory, and integral equations.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] At Chicago, Moore supervised 31 doctoral dissertations, including those of George Birkhoff, Leonard Dickson, Robert Lee Moore (no relation), and Oswald Veblen.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Birkhoff and Veblen went on to lead departments at Harvard and Princeton, respectively.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Dickson became the first great American algebraist and number theorist.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] According to the Mathematics Genealogy Project, as of December 2023, E.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Moore convinced the New York Mathematical Society to change its name to the American Mathematical Society, whose Chicago branch he led.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He presided over the AMS, 1901–02, and edited the *Transactions of the American Mathematical Society*, 1899–1907.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He was elected to the National Academy of Sciences, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] He was an Invited Speaker at the International Congress of Mathematicians in 1908 in Rome and in 1912 in Cambridge, England.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] In 2002, the American Mathematical Society established the E.
[src:e-h-moore/e-h-moore] Moore Research Article Prize in his honor.
